<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="255" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[118,768,1866,1955]" lastBlockId="4.[843,1494,281,370]" pageId="4" pageNumber="255">
An annual herbaceous plant that can reach 
<quantity box="[618,660,1866,1890]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="255" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
in height, apparently glabrous, lightly pubescent; it lives in warm and temperate America; a frequent weed in cropland and in modified soils (
<bibRefCitation author="CABRERA, A. L." box="[1008,1233,281,305]" pageId="4" pageNumber="255" pagination="292 - 493" refId="ref9627" refString="CABRERA, A. L. (1983). Solanaceae. Fl. Jujuy 8: 292 - 493." type="journal article" year="1983">CABRERA, 1983: 446</bibRefCitation>
). The Toba-Pilagá report that the ripe fruits are tasty and are gathered to be eaten raw (
<figureCitation box="[851,974,346,370]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[103,128,1873,1893]" captionTargetBox="[102,1479,279,1774]" captionTargetId="figure-62@5.[242,1339,368,1685]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 2. - Physalis viscosa L. A. A Maká Indian offers information about the plant; C. Ripe fruit with remains of the accrescent calyx; E. A Choroti Indian shows a branch of the plant. Physalis angulata L.; B, D. Branch with fruit. [Photos. A, E: P. Arenas; B-D: V. Friesen]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5748014" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5748014/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="255">Fig. 2 B, D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
